Here’s what body positivity is to me:

✨accepting and loving your body for where it is at this current moment in time

✨healing your body and treating it like a temple, but not getting down on yourself for every little ‘imperfection’

✨learning to love our bodies for how they were built, and recovering from the narrative that your body has to look a certain way for it to be a ‘good body’

Despite some people’s beliefs (cough cough trolls), loving your body does not mean giving up on it.

It doesn’t mean you never work out, or you only eat super unhealthy foods.

It doesn’t mean that you don’t care about your body.

Let’s appreciate the body that we have, because it’s so so important. Our bodies give us life. They carry us day to day. They allow us to talk long walks, cook yummy food, and love one another.

But can we please for the love of god let go of the narrative that body positivity = fat and unhealthy. This is not black and white.

Thank you to everyone who takes the time to understand this, and to those who don’t, well…. I may be fat but you’ll always be a bully 👏🏼

#bodypositivity #recovery #selflove #loveyourbody #bopo #hatersgonnahate #plussizeedition #fatlove

The first photo was taken in 2014 and I was 20 years old.

The second photo was taken in 2022, at 28 years old.

I’m here to tell you that bodies change, and that’s okay.

We grow older, and that’s ok.

When I was 20, I thought I was morbidly obese. I wasted years worrying about my body, spending hours and hours in the gym, and avoiding ‘bad’ foods.

Now at 28, my body may look different, but I am soooo much happier than I was at 20. I’m more confident. I do what I want, and stand up for myself, because I feel like I’m worth it.

It’s time to let go of our ideas of what a ‘good’ body is and start embracing our bodies for what they are in this very moment.

No matter what your body looks like, you are worthy. You are worthy of love and friendship and being treated like a human. You are worthy of living your life, eating whatever you want, and loving yourself.

And as January comes closer, don’t let anybody tell you that you have to change your body in 2023. You do you babes 💕

**not a pregnancy announcement**

The second that little pink line showed up I was ready. Ready for this adventure, ready to welcome a little baby into our lives and our hearts.

But just as quickly as it came, it was taken away.

I went in for my hormone testing and it just wasn’t rising like it should.

After about a week of being in absolute denial, my mind and my body finally accepted that this pregnancy wasn’t meant to be.

My body let go, but my mind still clings to the ‘what ifs’

What would we have been with this baby? Who was this baby? Were they a boy or a girl? Would they be bubbly and excited like me, or more quiet and logic-driven like John?

We discussed every possible detail in the happy week we lived in bliss before it was all taken away.

My heart hurts for what I’ll never know. I’m grieving for the life I saw so clearly, and the family members we told who were just as excited as we were.

I had no idea that this kind of pain followed a loss so inconsequential to so many people.

So here I am with a hole in my heart, unsure of where to go from here. It feels like my world stopped turning, and yet people are still living.

I’m sharing this because I need closure. I need proof that this was real, that I didn’t just exist in a dream and then a nightmare the past week.

I know we’ll have our rainbow baby one day, and I cannot WAIT. But for now, we grieve what we cannot have. 

Sending love to any of you out there who have also gone through this. 1 in 4 of us go through this. It’s so unfair.

💔💔💔

Xx Hannah
